article.description:
Cappie Pondexter hit a 3-pointer with 5.8 seconds
left and then stole the inbound pass to lift the Phoenix Mercury past the Minnesota Lynx 81-78 Wednesday.
article.headline: Pondexter's late 3-pointer pushes Mercury past Lynx
article.linkText: Pondexter's late 3-pointer pushes Mercury past Lynx
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Cappie Pondexter doesn't have any rookie jitters
about getting the ball in key situations.

Pondexter hit a 3-pointer with 5.8 seconds left and then stole
the inbound pass to lift the Phoenix Mercury to an 81-78 victory
over the Minnesota Wednesday.

"I like to take the big shots," Pondexter said. "I don't
mind. I love it when the game is close like that."

The Mercury overcame the poor shooting of their top two scorers
-- Diana Taurasi (4-for-16) and Pondexter (5-for-14) -- to win for
the sixth time in nine games. Taurasi was limited by foul trouble
and Pondexter picked up her fifth with 6:41 to play.

The rest of the Mercury were 20-for 39 from the field, led by
Kelly Miller's 17 points and seven rebounds.

Pondexter finished with 19 points, Taurasi with 13 points and
five assists.

Seimone Augustus had 24 points and eight rebounds for the Lynx,
who have lost four of their last five. Reserve center Vanessa
Hayden added 18 points and eight rebounds.

Taurasi said although another play was called, there was no
hesitation about Pondexter getting the ball.

"Without a doubt," Taurasi said. "With this team we have
three people who are confident enough to take that last shot and
bury it."

Phoenix called a timeout after Nicole Ohlde made a layup with
9.2 seconds remaining that tied the score at 78.

On the next play, Pondexter passed the ball in to Kristen
Rasmussen, who handed it back to Pondexter despite two Lynx players
in front of the Mercury rookie. Pondexter hit the 22-footer.

"Its something me and (Rasmussen) do a lot," Pondexter said.
"In case the first or second option don't go, I knew once Raz got
it, it would come back to me."

Taurasi laughed about it later.

"We didn't call that play but we work on that play every day,"
Taurasi said. "So it's kind of funny how that ended up winning the
game for us."

After Pondexter's shot, Augustus inbounded for Minnesota with
4.8 seconds remaining but ended up trying a crosscourt pass that
Pondexter got her hands on.

"We were just trying to get a shooter open any way possible but
it didn't happen," Augustus said. "We had two other shooters in
the game capable of knocking 3-point shots, it was just a matter of
getting the shooters open to take the shot."

The score was tied at 66 with 6:12 left before Phoenix went
7-for-9 from the free-throw line to take a 75-67 lead with 3:24
remaining.

"Our goal has been just to become a respectable team by getting
close to that .500 mark," Phoenix coach Paul Westhead said. "So
that's the short-term goal and we are getting closer. We are one
game away now. But our players have been playing pretty good
basketball for the last four weeks. So I am happy for them.

"This is a big win over Minnesota because down the stretch if
we are involved (in a playoff chase), it could be us and them."

Miller was 7-for-13 from the field in her second start since
coming back from a partially torn right hamstring.

"My teammates were getting me the ball and I kind of felt it,"
Miller said. "My super shot felt good and luckily they were going
in."

Minnesota erased an early 11-point deficit by going 8-for-13
from the field during one stretch and using a 10-2 run to take a
30-26 lead with 4:22 left in the half.

"Offensively, we were just too stagnant," Lynx coach Suzie
McConnell Serio said. "We addressed it in every time out, but we
just didn't have enough momentum."

Phoenix has scored 80 or more points 10 times in 13 games,
breaking the franchise mark of nine times during the 2000 season.
